## **Workshop Objectives**

---

1. Understand the concept of **branches** in Git.
2. Learn to create, switch, and manage branches.
3. Use GitHub to open and review **pull requests** (PRs).

## **Where we are now**

---

1. Basic familiarity with Git and GitHub (e.g., cloning, committing, and pushing changes).
2. Git installed on local machines.
3. GitHub accounts and access to a shared repository.
4. A code editor (e.g., VS Code).

## STEP 1 ‚Äî Forking and cloning a Github repo

---

1. **Fork the Repository to make a copy in your Github account**
    - [**https://github.com/AnnieCannons/nasa-apod-app**](https://github.com/AnnieCannons/nasa-apod-app)
2. **Clone the Repository into your local machine**

    2. Open the Terminal
    3. `cd` to into your `dev` folder, which is where you want to clone the repo
    4. Type¬†`git clone YOUR_REPO_URL` , replacing `YOUR_REPO_URL` with your Github repo link that you copied
    5. Press Enter to run the command
    6. Now you‚Äôve cloned your Github repo! üéâ
3. **In the Terminal, `cd` into your newly cloned project folder**
4. **Install npm packages and run the server to view your project** 
    1. Run `npm install` to install the npm packages
    2. Run `npm run dev` to start the server and view your project‚Äôs preview in the browser 
5. **Browse the code files to understand what the code is doing.** 
Imagine you‚Äôre working as a developer, and you‚Äôve just been assigned a task to build a new feature on this project. Your first step, before writing new code, is to familiarize yourself with the existing code!

## STEP 2 ‚Äî Making a new branch in your Github repo

---

1. **Create a branch to create your new feature ‚Äúyesterday-image‚Äù**
    
    ```bash
    git checkout -b yesterday-image
    ```
    
2. **Verify the branch was created successfully:**
    
    ```bash
    git branch
    ```
    
    - This command will open up a lightweight text editor called LESS, which is an application that lives within the terminal.
    - To exit LESS and go back to the command line, press the `q` key on your keyboard.
    
    ![image.png](Github%20Workshop%20Branches%20&%20Pull%20Requests%20191bb7044bb18082b875e86e3d6c51d9/image%201.png)
    
3. **Make sure you‚Äôve switched to your new branch on VS Code**
    - In the bottom left corner of VS Code, you should see the name of your new branch ‚Äúyesterday-image‚Äù. This indicates that you have switched to your new branch on VS Code.
        
        ![image.png](Github%20Workshop%20Branches%20&%20Pull%20Requests%20191bb7044bb18082b875e86e3d6c51d9/image%202.png)
        
    - If it says ‚Äúmain‚Äù instead of ‚Äúyesterday-image‚Äù, that means you are currently on the main branch. Click on the branch name to switch the branch you‚Äôre on in VS Code.
    - From now on, you should always check which branch you‚Äôre in before you write any code ‚Äî you don‚Äôt want to accidentally write code in the wrong branch! Generally, you only write code in a feature branch or a develop branch, never in the main branch.

## STEP 3 ‚Äî Getting an API key and keeping it secure in a .env file

---

1. **Generate a NASA API Key** 
    
    Go to [api.nasa.gov](http://api.nasa.gov) to generate an API key that will be emailed to you. Copy the API key value. 
    
2. **Make your .env file**
    
    Go back to VS Code and make a .env file in the root folder of your project.
    
    In your .env file, define your API key variable like this. It should be called `VITE_API_KEY` and its value should be the API key you copied in your email. 
    
    ![image.png](Github%20Workshop%20Branches%20&%20Pull%20Requests%20191bb7044bb18082b875e86e3d6c51d9/image%203.png)
    
3. **Add your .env file to the .gitignore file**
    
    Whenever you have an API key, it should be kept private, secure, hidden from public, and *not* published on Github. So, we need to add .env to the .gitignore file. This will tell Github to ignore the .env file so that it doesn‚Äôt get published publicly. 
    
    ![image.png](Github%20Workshop%20Branches%20&%20Pull%20Requests%20191bb7044bb18082b875e86e3d6c51d9/image%204.png)
    
4. **Use your API key in App.jsx**
    
    In the App.jsx file, we can set the `NASA_KEY` variable on line 16 to hold our API key variable that we created in our .env file. To do this, you need to prefix the variable name with `import.meta.env` like this: 
    
    ![image.png](Github%20Workshop%20Branches%20&%20Pull%20Requests%20191bb7044bb18082b875e86e3d6c51d9/image%205.png)
    
    Vite will automatically know how to pull in our environment variables from the .env file as long as we put `import.meta.env` beforehand. 
    

## STEP 4 ‚Äî Build a new feature in your `yesterday-image` branch

---

**The new feature we will be building is a yesterday image feature.**

- As a user, when I open the side menu bar, I should see a button that says ‚ÄúGet Yesterday‚Äôs Image‚Äù. When I click the button, the previous days image should appear

    

## STEP 5 ‚Äî **Merging the feature branch into your main branch**

---

Here‚Äôs the step-by-step code for merging one branch into another using Git. The following assumes you‚Äôre working with the `yesterday-image` and want to merge it into the `main` branch.

### **Merging a Branch into Another**

**1. Switch to the Target Branch (e.g., `main`)**

Run the following command to switch to the branch you want to merge into:

```bash
git checkout main
```

**2. Update the Target Branch**

Make sure your `main` branch is up-to-date with the latest changes from the remote by *pulling* the code: 

```bash
git pull origin main
```

**3. Merge the Specified Branch into the Current branch**

This command will merge the specified branch (which is `yesterday-image`) into the current branch (which is `main`)

```bash
git merge yesterday-image
```

- If there are no conflicts, Git will merge the changes automatically.
- If conflicts exist, Git will show the conflicting files, and you‚Äôll need to resolve them before proceeding.
- **NOTE: In most cases, you would be merging into a ‚Äòdev‚Äô or ‚Äòdevelop‚Äô branch and not a ‚Äòmain‚Äô branch. We are doing this just as an example.**

**4. Push the Merged Changes to the Remote Repository**

After a successful merge, push the updated `main` branch to GitHub:

```
git push origin main
```

## STEP 6 ‚Äî Submit a Pull Request (PR)

---

1. **Navigate to your repository on the Github website** 
2. **Open the Pull Requests Tab:**
    - Click on the **Pull Requests** tab in the repository.
3. **Start a New Pull Request:**
    - Click the **New Pull Request** button.
4. **Select the Branches to Compare:**
    
    ![image.png](Github%20Workshop%20Branches%20&%20Pull%20Requests%20191bb7044bb18082b875e86e3d6c51d9/image%206.png)
    
5. **Review the Changes:**
    - GitHub will display a summary of the changes.
    - Ensure the listed changes match your expectations.
6. **Add a Title and Description:**
    - Write a descriptive title (e.g., ‚ÄúAdd yesterday image feature‚Äù).
    - Provide a detailed description of the changes, including:
        - The purpose of the changes.
        - Any key features or fixes.
        - Any dependencies or testing instructions.
7. **Submit the Pull Request:**
    - Click the **Create Pull Request** button.

# Recap

---

Let‚Äôs review what we did in this workshop: 

- Fork - Full copy of a repo from a remote to a remote
- Clone - Full copy of a repo from a remote repo to our local machine
- NPM Install - Installs all the dependencies (all the code my code needs) as listed in the package.json
- Branch checkout - Create a new branch, allows us to work on our entire project in a separate workstream
- Commit + Push to our feature branch
- Change back into the main branch
- Pull the code on the main branch - to make sure we are all up to date
- Merged - Pull all our feature branch code into our main branch
- Push to main branch
- Submitted a pull request
